The Making of Saint Louis — St. Louis Public Library - City|https://slpl.bibliocommons.com/v2/record/S198C464696|LouisThe Making of Saint Louis Kingship, Sanctity, and Crusade in the Later Middle Ages Gaposchkin, M. Cecilia (Marianne Cecilia), 1970-Gaposchkin, M. Cecilia (Marianne Cecilia), 1970- Title rated 0 out of 5 stars, based on 0 ratings(0 ratings) You have not rated this title. Rate this titleRate this  ...    Canonized in 1297 as Saint Louis, King Louis IX of France (r. 1226-1270) was one of the most important kings of medieval history and also one of the foremost saints of the later Middle Ages. As a saint, Louis became the centerpiece of an ideological program that buttressed the ongoing political consolidation of France and underscored Capetian claims of sacred kingship. M. Cecilia Gaposchkin reconstructs and analyzes the process that led to the monarch's canonization and the consolidation and spread of his cult. Differing political and religious ideals produced competing images of the sanctity of Louis in late-thirteenth and early fourteenth-century France. Drawing on hagiography,
